AGI - The police arrested an Afghan asylum seeker on the scene of what the German leaders defined a "attack" with a car l>anciata on the crowd wounding 28 people, some seriously, in Munich. The attack on the eve of a high-profile conference on security in the Bavarian city and in the context of a heated debate on immigration in view of the elections of 23 February, after a series of similar attacks.
The vehicle, a Mini Cooper, is populated on a union event, leaving a trail of wounded and their things scattered on the street, including a baby stroller. The police shot against the unconscious car and arrested the driver, a 24-year-old Afghan asylum seeker who the German media identified as Farhad N.
Chancellor Olaf Scholz condemned the "terrible" attack > and promised severe consequences. "From my point of view it is quite clear: This attacker cannot count on any pity, he must be punished and must leave the country," said Scholz to journalists.
Shoes, glasses and baby stroller > were left out in the wake of the suspect attack, which follows the deadly fury of a car in a Christmas market in the eastern city of Magdeburg in December.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
The 24-year-old Afghan asylum seeker, who lives in Monaco, was arrested on the scene after law enforcement once shot against the car, but without hitting it. The authorities have "departments of an extremist motive" and the investigation was entrusted to the regional prosecutor, they added. A firefighter spokesman said that many of the wounded were "gravely injured, some in danger of life".
The suspect would arrive in Germany in 2016, at the height of the massive influx of migrants in Europe. His request for asylum would have been rejected by the German authorities, but the repatriation was not foreseen. Bavarian Premier Markus Soeder told reporters that the incident was "simply terrible" and that "it seems to be an attack".
"This is not the first accident... We must demonstrate with determination that something will change in Germany," said Soeder, whose CSU party is allied with the conservative CDU at national level. "This is another proof that we cannot continue to move from one attack to another."
The CDU/CSU alliance, which according to the polls is on the right track to win the elections that will take place within a few more than a week, asked to tighten immigration restrictions after recent attacks. Under pressure on this issue before the election was convened, Scholz's government moved to make asylum rules more stringent and speed up expulsions, even in Afghanistan.&nbsp; Scholz today said that repatriations are "complicated" to be organized, but that the government "is going to do it in other cases not only once, but on a continuous basis".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
On December 21, a Saudi doctor threw himself &nbsp; with a suv on the crowd making purchases between the Christmas market stalls in Magdeburg: 5 people were killed and the wounded were over 200. No link has ever been established between man and Islamic extremist organizations: the attacker accused the German authorities of not doing enough to defend Saudi women.&nbsp;

