AGI -&nbsp; It seems to be dismantled, at least for now, the dream of Herbert Kickl to become 'Volkskanzler' (the Chancellor of the People). After more than five weeks of negotiations with the people of the OeVP, the leader of the Freedom Party (OeVP) raised a white flag. The negotiations of the possible 'Blau-Schwarz' coalition (blue-black) failed, when Kickl resigned the mandate to form the government conferred on him on 6 January by federal President Alexander Van der Bellen.<br> At this point, Austria may soon return to the polls. >
&nbsp;
According to the polls, the Freedom Party will be strengthened by the vote while the people are in free fall. It is not therefore said that Kickl must always set aside the aspiration to become 'the gatekeeper of the people', as a century ago he called himself Adolf Hitler.
&nbsp;
Surely a delicate moment for Austria, the nation has always been a friend of Italy. From September 5, 1946, with the Paris Peace Agreement (De Gasperi-Gruber), Austria has played the role of 'Schutzmachtfunktion', or the South Tyrol-South Tyrolean power.
<br The epilogue of the crisis comes after complicated months for Austrian politics. >
&nbsp;
<h2> The stages of the crisis
These stages since September 29 last year, when the FFP had arrived first in political elections, to date.
<br> - 29 September 2024: in the elections, the FPOe is the strongest party in parliament with 28.8% of votes, followed by the people of the OeVP (26.3%), the Social-Democrats of the SPOe (21.1%) and the Liberals of Neos (9.1%). In the aftermath of the vote, there are three two-party coalitions taken into account: FPOe-OeVP, FPOe-SPOe and, with an extremely reduced majority, OeVP-SPOe.
- 4 October: President Van der Bellen starts the first consultations with the five parliamentary parties.<br> - 9 October: After the first round of talks, Van der Bellen invites party leaders with more votes, FPOe, OeVP and SPOe, to "claim what kind of collaboration would be impotible to solve the stalemate." <br> - 15 October: Kickl and the popular leader and Chancellor Karl Nehammer are seen to discuss a possible understanding. Nehammer concludes a coalition with the FPOe led by Kickl.<br> - 18 October: Kickl and Andreas Babler (SPOe) meet but also the leader of the Social Democrats excludes any collaboration with the FPOe.<br> - 22 October: After a second round of talks, Van der Bellen entrusts Nehammer to form a government and asks him to start negotiations with the SPOe.&nbsp;
- 25 October: Exploratory talks between OeVP and SPOe.<br> - 12 November: OeVP and SPOe invite Neos to sit at the negotiating table as a third partner.<br> - 18 November: Nehammer, Babler and Beate Meinl-Reisinger (Neos) announce the beginning of the negotiations.<br> - 2 December: the budgetary situation puts hard evidence of the climate of the coalition: the SPOe threatens to suspend coalition talks.<br> - 16 December: the European Commission proposes four possible rehabilitation paths. Within four or seven years, Austria will have to save between 18 and 24 billion euros.<br> - 3 January 2025: Meinl-Reisinger announces the withdrawal of Neos from coalition negotiations: lacks the will of the other two political forces to implement fundamental reforms. OeVP and SPOe decide to continue the negotiations. Nehammer interrupts talks with the SPOe and announces his resignation from both Chancellor and Leader of the OeVP.<br> - 5 January: Nehammer resigns from the task of forming the government. The OeVP chooses a new interim party leader, Christian Stocker, who claims to be willing to accept any FPOe offer for coalition negotiations.<br> - 6 January: After a talk lasted about an hour between Federal President Van der Bellen and FPOe's leader, Kickl, the head of state announced that he had given the Freedom Party a mandate to form a government. "I did not take this step lightly," explains Van der Bellen.<br> - 7 January: Kickl invites people to negotiate. Stocker accepts the offer of the FPOe and in the evening the two leaders meet. Meanwhile, thousands of people manifest in Vienna and other Austrian cities against a blue-black government.<br> - 10 January: President Van der Bellen entrusts the government's leadership to Foreign Minister Alexander Schallenberg (OeVP). Meanwhile, FPOe and OeVP deal with the formation of the coalition. - 13 January: FPOe and OeVP announce an agreement on a common route to be sent to Brussels to avoid an excessive deficit procedure. the European Commission declares that, after examining the measures, an excessive deficit procedure will not be initiated at the moment towards Austria. the subgroups of the two parties begin their work.<br> - 25 January: the request of the leader of the OeVP Stocker to the Freedom Party to correct the route creates fibrillation in the FPOe.<br> - 5 February: after 129 days there is still no government: a record in the Second Republic. The precedent dates back to 1962 when the government was formed on 129th day.<br> - 6 February: Kickl and Stocker announce that the negotiations for the coalition, interrupted because of important differences, will resume.<br> - 9 February: the differences between FPOe and OeVP remain great. The dispute continues on the Ministry of the Interior, which both claim.<br> - 10 February: night meeting between the two leaders, but nothing in fact.<br> - 11 February: signals of a breakup are very strong. The tones from the OeVP files are hard, but the two leaders assure President Van der Bellen that the negotiations are still in progress.<br> - 12 February: the break is official. Kickl resigns the task of forming the government.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>var der Bellen: "I have 4 options, I will evaluate..."</h2>
The Austrian Federal President Alexander van der Bellen has announced that in the coming days he will start talks > with party leaders to assess pros and against four possible options to overcome the impasse in the formation of a new government. "My task is to ensure that the country has a government capable of acting," Van der Bellen said, after FPOe's leader, Herbert Kickl, resigned the position > to form an executive coalition with the OeVP people.<br> "The first option is that the National Council (the Lower Chamber of the Austrian Parliament, ndr) decides to indict new elections, > the second would be a minority government with the support of Parliament, the third a government of experts, > the fourth that one can find a majority," explained the president talking to the country.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

