AGI - In the heart of Africa, the fate of thousands of textile workers of the factory of jeans Wrangler and Levi's is hung on a thread: to the decision of President Donald Trump on the eventual extension of Agoa>, due in September. The African Growth and Opportunity Act (Agoa), a 25-year agreement, guarantees African products access to the US market free of duties. The 'Made in Africa' jeans are made in a factory located on the outskirts of Nairobi, Kenya's capital, respecting a strict American tradition and the garments are intended for chains such as Walmart and JC Penny in the United States. The United Aryan clothing exporter owes its existence to the Agora, now at risk. From the decision taken by President Trump will depend in general on the support of millions of Africans, including the thousands of employees of United Aryan. Every year from the factory, up to 8 million pairs of jeans are sent to the United States, as well as millions of shirts and other items. An average assembly line worker earns the equivalent of about 190 euros per month. "We have 150,000 people who depend directly or indirectly on us," says CEO Pankaj Bedi, pointing out that his establishment "has stabilized the entire socio-economic situation of the region".
&nbsp;
The area was dangerous before United Aryan began production operations in 2002. "The gangs had stolen everything, even copper cables. Today our families are happy, our children go to school, crime has decreased," said Norah Nasimiyu, 48 years old, representative of jeans workers. Every day thousands of people gather in front of the gates of the factory, hoping to replace the absentes among the approximately 10,000 employees.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The factory has already faced serious challenges: in 2005, the abolition of the quota regime which had regulated textile trade for decades has flooded markets with Asian clothing. The financial crisis of 2008 and the Covid-19 pandemic almost blocked it. Today the factory is burdened with the answer to a question: will the United States renew or not the Agora? Without the advantage of duty-free, US buyers will definitely turn to cheaper solutions in Asia, turning their backs on Africa. While Republicans and Democrats seemed to be in favour of extending the agreements during the last year's negotiations, their survival now seems threatened by Trump's return to the White House, by its openly skeptical position on free trade and its harsh duty line.
&nbsp;
The United States takes advantage of the cheaper labour in Africa, especially in the textile sector, cost-sensitive, according to Bedassa Tadesse, professor of Economics at the University of Minnesota in Duluth. "But we have come to a point where commercial policy decisions are no longer based solely on cost-benefit analysis," he says. However, there is hope: Trump might consider Agora as a means to counter Chinese influence in Africa. "This is a very important tool in relations between the United States and Africa, especially now that we have just lost virtually all of our soft power by dismantling Usaid," highlights Witney Schneidman, Agoa expert at the think tank of the Brookings Institution. But "this is a small change in Trump's world vision," far from being a priority, he says. Negotiations are ongoing for United Aryan, within the Kenya Manufacturing Association. "In America we cannot produce what we produce," says CEO Pankaj Bedi. The time strings and the plant at the door of Kenya and its customers must know the fate of the Agora by the end of March>, so that they can plan the next season, otherwise the production lines will stop. Buyers started panicking, but "we assured them that everything would go well. We cross our fingers!", concluded Bedi.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
